# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1930-british-empire-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The **1928 Summer Olympics** (Dutch: *Olympische Zomerspelen 1928*), officially the **Games of the IX Olympiad** (Dutch: *Spelen van de IXe Olympiade*), was an international multi-sport event that was celebrated from 28 July to 12 August 1928 in Amsterdam, Netherlands.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The city of Amsterdam had previously bid for the 1920 and 1924 Olympic Games.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Still, it was obliged to give way to war-torn Antwerp in Belgium for the 1920 Games and Pierre de Coubertin's Paris for the 1924 Games.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The only other candidate city for the 1928 Olympics was Los Angeles, which would eventually be selected to host the Olympics four years later.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] In preparation for the 1932 Summer Olympics, the United States Olympic Committee reviewed the costs and revenue of the 1928 Games.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The committee reported a total cost of US$1.183 million with receipts of US$1.165 million, giving a negligible loss of US$18,000, which was a considerable improvement over the 1924 Games.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold and medals overall.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Dutch nobleman Frederik van Tuyll van Serooskerken first proposed Amsterdam as the host city for the Summer Olympic Games in 1912, even before the Netherlands Olympic Committee was established.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The Olympic Games were canceled in 1916 due to World War I.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] In 1919, the Netherlands Olympic Committee abandoned the proposal of Amsterdam in favor of their support for the nomination of Antwerp as host city for the 1920 Summer Olympics.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] In 1921, Paris was selected for the 1924 Summer Olympics on the condition that the 1928 Summer Olympics would be organized in Amsterdam.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] This decision, supported by the Netherlands Olympic Committee, was announced by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) on 2 June 1921.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Los Angeles' bid for the 1928 Summer Olympics was unsuccessful in 1922 and again in 1923.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The city was eventually selected as host city for the 1932 Summer Olympics, being the only bidder for that year.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] During the 1928 Summer Olympics, there were 14 sports, 20 disciplines and 109 events in the tournament.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] In parentheses is the number of events per discipline.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Women's athletics and team gymnastics debuted at these Olympics, in spite of criticism.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Five women's athletics events were added: 100 meters, 800 meters, high jump, discus, and 400 meter hurdles.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] In protest of the limited number of events, British women athletes, boycotted the Games.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Halina Konopacka of Poland became the first female Olympic track and field champion.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Reports that the 800 meter run ended with several of the competitors being completely exhausted were widely (and erroneously) circulated.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] As a result, the IOC decided that women were too frail for long-distance running, and women's Olympic running events were limited to 200 meters until the 1960s.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Tennis disappeared from the program until it reappeared in 1968 as a demonstration sport.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] These Games also included art competitions in five categories: architecture, painting, sculpture, literature, and music.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] However, the IOC no longer considers these to be official medal events, so the medals awarded are not included in today's Olympic medal counts.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Fourteen sports venues were used for the 1928 Summer Olympics.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The Swim Stadium was demolished in 1929.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The Het Kasteel football stadium was renovated in 1998–99.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The Monnikenhuize stadium was demolished in 1950.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The Schermzaal sports hall has also been demolished.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The Olympic Stadium was renovated between 1996 and 2000, and is still in use.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The Old Stadion was demolished in 1929 and replaced with housing in the Amsterdam area.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Many cars were expected for the Games, but Amsterdam had at most 2,000 single-car parking spaces.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Consequently, several new parking sites were provided, and a special parking symbol was launched to show foreign visitors where they could park.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The white P on a blue background was to become the international traffic sign for parking, and is still used today.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Athletics events were held on a 400-meter track, later becoming the standard for athletics tracks.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Map of the Amsterdam region with Olympic venues marked.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Map of the Netherlands with Olympic venues marked.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] A total of 46 nations were represented at the Amsterdam Games.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Malta, Panama, and Rhodesia (now Zimbabwe) competed at the Olympic Games for the first time.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Germany returned after having been banned in 1920 and 1924.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The nations that participated in the previous games in Paris 1924 but were absent in Amsterdam 1928 were Brazil and Ecuador.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] At the time, Australia, New Zealand, Canada, South Africa and Ireland were all dominions of the British Empire.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] India and Rhodesia were also a part of the British Empire, but were not dominions.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] United States, France, Argentina, Japan, etc.) and the international community as a whole (i.e.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] League of Nations) the term dominion, used internally in the British Empire, was very ambiguous, meaning "something between a colony and state".
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] It was only years later with the Statute of Westminster 1931 that this ambiguity would be dispelled.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Philippines was an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1928 Games.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The official poster for the Games displaying a running man in a white shirt was designed by Jos Rovers however the IOC never succeeded in obtaining the copyright of the image.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The IOC used a different poster, with the German text *Olympische Spiele*, and an athlete partly covered in the Dutch national flag, holding a peace leaf in his hand.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The poster was made for a German book about the Amsterdam Olympics.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] The last living competitor of the 1928 Summer Olympics was Carla Marangoni, a member of the silver medal-winning Italian gymnastic team who had been twelve years old during the Olympics.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1928-summer-olympics] Marangoni died 18 January 2018, at the age of 102 as the oldest living Olympic medalist at the time of her death.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1930-british-empire-games] The **1930 British Empire Games** were the inaugural edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, and was held in Hamilton, Ontario, from 16 to 23 August 1930.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was organized by *Hamilton Spectator* sportswriter Bobby Robinson after he attended the 1928 Summer Olympics in Amsterdam as manager of the Canadian track and field team and was inspired to create a similar event for the British Empire.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1930-british-empire-games] After campaigning for the idea among contacts he met at the Olympics, he was asked to organise the first British Empire Games in Hamilton.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1930-british-empire-games] Fellow Hamilton journalist Ivan Miller helped with the organizing committee.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1930-british-empire-games] The sports included athletics, boxing, lawn bowls, rowing, swimming, and wrestling.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1930-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony and athletics events were held at Civic Stadium (later renamed Ivor Wynne Stadium) in east Hamilton.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was opened by the Governor General of Canada, Lord Willingdon, on 16 August.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1930-british-empire-games] Canadian triple jumper Gordon Smallacombe claimed the debut gold medal a few hours later.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1930-british-empire-games] The 1930 British Empire Games made use of pedestals for dignitaries to present medals to winning athletes, as proposed by Bobby Robinson.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1930-british-empire-games] This inspired the Olympic medal podium ceremonies which began at the 1932 Winter Olympics.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1932-winter-olympics] The **1932 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **III Olympic Winter Games** and commonly known as **Lake Placid 1932**, were a winter multi-sport event in the United States, held in Lake Placid, New York, United States.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1932-winter-olympics] The games opened on February 4 and closed on February 13.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1932-winter-olympics] It was the first time the Winter Games were held outside of Europe and the first of four Winter Olympics held in the United States; Lake Placid hosted again in 1980.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1932-winter-olympics] The games were awarded to Lake Placid in part by the efforts of Godfrey Dewey, head of the Lake Placid Club and son of Melvil Dewey, inventor of the Dewey Decimal System.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1932-winter-olympics] California also had a bid for the 1932 Winter Games.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1932-winter-olympics] William May Garland, president of the California X Olympiad Association, wanted the games to take place in Wrightwood and Big Pines, California.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1932-winter-olympics] The world's largest ski jump at the time was constructed in Big Pines for the event, but the games were ultimately awarded to Lake Placid.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1932-winter-olympics] The practice of awarding Olympic medals at podium ceremonies was established at the 1932 Winter Olympics, based on pedestals used at the 1930 British Empire Games, as proposed by Melville Marks Robinson.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1932-winter-olympics] Medals were awarded in 14 events contested in 4 sports (7 disciplines).
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1932-winter-olympics] The Games also included events in three demonstration sports.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1932-winter-olympics] Athletes from 17 nations competed in these Games, down from 25 nations at the previous Games in 1928.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1932-winter-olympics] Argentina, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Luxembourg, Mexico, the Netherlands, and Yugoslavia did not send athletes to Lake Placid.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1934-british-empire-games] The **1934 British Empire Games** were the second edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, held in England, from 4–11 August 1934.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1934-british-empire-games] The host city was London, with the main venues at Wembley Park and the White City Stadium, although the track cycling events were in Manchester.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1934-british-empire-games] Seventeen national teams took part, including the Irish Free State (the only Games in which they participated, although an all-Ireland team competed at the 1930 Games).
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1934-british-empire-games] The 1934 Games had been originally awarded to Johannesburg, South Africa, but the change of venue to London was made due to concerns regarding the treatment of black and Asian athletes by South African officials and fans.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1934-british-empire-games] Six sports were featured in the Games with rowing being dropped from 1930 but cycling making its first appearance.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1934-british-empire-games] Athletics took place at the White City Stadium, while boxing, wrestling, and aquatics (swimming and diving) were held at the Wembley Empire Pool, where the swimming pool would be converted overnight into an arena with 7,000 additional seats brought in to increase the capacity to 12,000.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1934-british-empire-games] Lawn bowls was held at two clubs in Paddington and Temple, while the cycling was held at the Fallowfield Stadium in Manchester.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1934-british-empire-games] Events for women athletes included a debut in athletics; the previous games had women's events in swimming and diving only.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1934-british-empire-games] The Wembley Empire Pool was built specifically for the games on the instruction of Arthur Elvin and had been completed in just nine months, opening 10 days before the start of the Games on 25 July.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1934-british-empire-games] (Teams participating for the first time in **bold**).
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1938-british-empire-games] The **1938 British Empire Games** were the third British Empire Games, the event that evolved to become the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1938-british-empire-games] Held in Sydney, Australia, from 5–12 February 1938, they were timed to coincide with Sydney's sesqui-centenary (150 years since the foundation of British settlement in Australia).
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1938-british-empire-games] Venues included the Sydney Cricket Ground (the main stadium), the North Sydney Olympic Pool and Henson Park.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1938-british-empire-games] An estimated 40,000 people attended the opening ceremony.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1938-british-empire-games] A men's residential village was established within the grounds of the Sydney Showground, while the female athletes were housed in hotels.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1938-british-empire-games] The star of the games was the Australian athlete Decima Norman, who won five gold medals in track and field.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1938-british-empire-games] Margaret Dovey, later married to Australian prime minister Gough Whitlam, finished sixth in the 220 yards breaststroke.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1938-british-empire-games] Due to the onset of World War II, the games were not held again until 1950.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1950-british-empire-games] The **1950 British Empire Games** were the fourth staging of what is now called the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1950-british-empire-games] It was held in Auckland, New Zealand, between 4 and 11 February 1950, after a 12-year gap from the third edition of the games due to World War II.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1950-british-empire-games] The fourth games were originally awarded to Montreal, Canada and were to be held in 1942 but were cancelled due to the War.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1950-british-empire-games] The Games were declared open by Sir Bernard Freyberg.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1950-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony was held at Eden Park and was sold out with 40,000 people attending.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1950-british-empire-games] Eden Park also served as the main venue, while the closing ceremonies were held at Western Springs Stadium.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1950-british-empire-games] Other venues included the Auckland Town Hall and the Newmarket Olympic Pool.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1950-british-empire-games] A 1950 British Empire Games documentary film of the games was made by the New Zealand National Film Unit.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1950-british-empire-games] At the 1950 British Empire Games all the teams won at least one medal.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Vancouver, British Columbia, from 30 July to 7 August 1954.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the fifth edition of the event that would eventually become known as the Commonwealth Games, the second post-war Games, the second Canadian Games after the inaugural event in Hamilton and the first event since the name change from British Empire Games took effect in 1952.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Other bids to stage the Games were received from Toronto, Montreal and Hamilton.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The main venue was the Empire Stadium, which had been specifically constructed for the games at the cost of £500,000.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Work on the 25,000 seated stadium started in October 1953 and the keys were handed over to Stan Smith (General chairman of the games) on 12 July 1954.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The games were attended by 24 nations and 662 competitors.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the first time that the games gained a television audience, when CBC and NBC transmitted pictures to an estimated 100 million North American viewers.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Recordings of the games were also shown on the BBC Television Service, beginning a consistent association between the BBC and the Commonwealth Games which only ended in 2026.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was at these games that the "Miracle Mile" took place between Roger Bannister and John Landy at the Empire Stadium.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the first time these two (and at that time the only two) sub-four-minute mile runners appeared in the same race, and also the first time two runners broke four minutes in the same race.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] On the same afternoon, Jim Peters, the holder of the world best time for the marathon, entered the stadium 17 minutes ahead of his nearest rival, but collapsed on his final lap, and never completed the race.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 24 teams were represented at the 1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** (Welsh: *Gemau Ymerodraeth Prydain a'r Gymanwlad* 1958) were held in Cardiff, Wales, from 18 to 26 July 1958.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the sixth edition of what would come to be known as the Commonwealth Games, the second Games held in the United Kingdom, and the second held under the name **British Empire and Commonwealth Games**.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Thirty-five nations sent a total of 1,130 athletes and 228 officials to the Cardiff Games and 23 countries and dependencies won medals, including, for the first time, Singapore, Ghana, Kenya and the Isle of Man.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 178,000 tickets were eventually sold during the Games.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The Cardiff Games introduced the Queen's Baton Relay, which has been conducted as a prelude to every Commonwealth Games ever since.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The British Empire and Commonwealth Games, including the opening and closing ceremonies, were held at the Cardiff Arms Park.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The following venues were used during the Games.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 36 countries and territories were represented (and 1,100 athletes), being the largest number to date, with a significant number of teams competing for the first time at the 1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] At Cardiff Arms Park, an anti-apartheid crowd protested at the all-white South African team; games organisers responded that non-white South Africans were ineligible as their associations were not affiliated to the international federations.
[src:1930-british-empire-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] South Africa left the Commonwealth in 1961 and next appeared at the Games in 1994.
